1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:03,600
 - Thank you, Patrick.

2
00:00:03,600 --> 00:00:04,440
 Good morning, UV.

3
00:00:04,440 --> 00:00:12,360
 (speaking in foreign language)

4
00:00:12,360 --> 00:00:14,800
 All right, so if you don't know this about me,

5
00:00:14,800 --> 00:00:17,160
 besides the things that you see me do here

6
00:00:17,160 --> 00:00:20,440
 on a Sunday morning, I also lead our youth group

7
00:00:20,440 --> 00:00:23,600
 and our kids ministry throughout the weekdays.

8
00:00:23,600 --> 00:00:24,760
 And working with these students,

9
00:00:24,760 --> 00:00:26,800
 one of the things that I realize is

10
00:00:26,800 --> 00:00:28,240
 the more I spend time with them,

11
00:00:28,240 --> 00:00:30,480
 the more I actually picked up some of the Gen Z

12
00:00:30,480 --> 00:00:32,320
 and Gen Alpha lingo.

13
00:00:32,320 --> 00:00:36,120
 And sometimes I even find myself speaking like them.

14
00:00:36,120 --> 00:00:40,040
 (speaking in foreign language)

15
00:00:40,040 --> 00:01:02,720
 So let me give you a few examples here.

16
00:01:02,720 --> 00:01:05,080
 When they say, "Oh, I'm so cooked,"

17
00:01:05,080 --> 00:01:07,320
 it doesn't mean that they're literally getting cooked,

18
00:01:07,320 --> 00:01:09,400
 but that means that they are in trouble

19
00:01:09,400 --> 00:01:11,440
 or they're just exhausted.

20
00:01:11,440 --> 00:01:13,480
 Or when they say, "This thing or this person

21
00:01:13,480 --> 00:01:15,280
 "looks kind of sus,"

22
00:01:15,280 --> 00:01:17,880
 it doesn't mean that, it just means that something

23
00:01:17,880 --> 00:01:20,880
 or someone is looking a little suspicious.

24
00:01:20,880 --> 00:01:22,320
 And sometimes they will even combine

25
00:01:22,320 --> 00:01:24,160
 a few of these slang together.

26
00:01:24,160 --> 00:01:28,400
 And for example, they will say, "This food is bomb, no cap."

27
00:01:28,400 --> 00:01:29,880
 Let me translate it for you.

28
00:01:29,880 --> 00:01:34,000
 That means, "This food is so good, I'm not even lying."

29
00:01:34,000 --> 00:01:57,720
 (speaking in foreign language)

30
00:01:57,720 --> 00:02:01,880
 So the reality is, we as human can be easily influenced

31
00:02:01,880 --> 00:02:05,040
 by our surrounding and the people that we spend time with,

32
00:02:05,040 --> 00:02:07,320
 whether it is for good or for worse.

33
00:02:07,320 --> 00:02:09,360
 And this is why there's a saying in Mandarin

34
00:02:09,360 --> 00:02:10,640
 that goes like this,

35
00:02:10,640 --> 00:02:13,560
 "He who stays near vermilion gets stained red,

36
00:02:13,560 --> 00:02:16,760
 "and he who stays near ink gets stained black."

37
00:02:16,760 --> 00:02:31,080
 (speaking in foreign language)

38
00:02:31,080 --> 00:02:33,920
 So this Sunday, we're actually going to begin a new series

39
00:02:33,920 --> 00:02:35,760
 in the Book of Judges.

40
00:02:35,760 --> 00:02:38,840
 I don't know how familiar you are with this book,

41
00:02:38,840 --> 00:02:40,960
 but maybe you have heard of the story of Samson,

42
00:02:40,960 --> 00:02:43,200
 who is one of the more popular judges.

43
00:02:43,200 --> 00:02:45,080
 Or if you have been to church for a while,

44
00:02:45,080 --> 00:02:48,360
 maybe you have heard of the story of Gideon and his army.

45
00:02:48,360 --> 00:02:49,960
 But there's actually a lot more to it

46
00:02:49,960 --> 00:02:52,200
 in the Book of Judges.

47
00:02:52,200 --> 00:03:11,480
 (speaking in foreign language)

48
00:03:11,480 --> 00:03:13,480
 So what I hope to do with this sermon series

49
00:03:13,480 --> 00:03:17,040
 is to help us situate these individual stories of judges

50
00:03:17,040 --> 00:03:19,040
 within the context of the whole book,

51
00:03:19,040 --> 00:03:21,080
 and also to understand the Book of Judges

52
00:03:21,080 --> 00:03:24,480
 within the larger framework of God's redemptive history

53
00:03:24,480 --> 00:03:26,160
 throughout the Bible.

54
00:03:26,160 --> 00:03:39,040
 (speaking in foreign language)

55
00:03:39,040 --> 00:03:41,320
 So what is the Book of Judges about?

56
00:03:41,320 --> 00:03:43,120
 As one scholar describes it,

57
00:03:43,120 --> 00:03:47,120
 at its core, the Book of Judges is about the canonization

58
00:03:47,120 --> 00:03:49,400
 of the people of Israel.

59
00:03:49,400 --> 00:03:50,400
 Or to put it another way,

60
00:03:50,400 --> 00:03:52,720
 it is about God's chosen people

61
00:03:52,720 --> 00:03:56,080
 becoming more and more like the idolatrous nation

62
00:03:56,080 --> 00:03:57,640
 around them.

63
00:03:57,640 --> 00:03:59,480
 And instead of fulfilling their calling

64
00:03:59,480 --> 00:04:02,480
 as a kingdom of peace and a holy nation,

65
00:04:02,480 --> 00:04:05,960
 and to show these nations around them what God is like,

66
00:04:05,960 --> 00:04:09,920
 judges actually show us God's people at its worst,

67
00:04:09,920 --> 00:04:12,180
 not just from a religious perspective,

68
00:04:12,180 --> 00:04:15,480
 but also from a moral point of view.

69
00:04:15,480 --> 00:04:19,400
 (speaking in foreign language)

70
00:04:19,400 --> 00:04:23,320
 (speaking in foreign language)

71
00:04:23,320 --> 00:04:27,240
 (speaking in foreign language)

72
00:04:27,240 --> 00:04:52,280
 So if you turn each individual book in the Bible

73
00:04:52,280 --> 00:04:54,960
 into a movie, I can bet you that Judges

74
00:04:54,960 --> 00:04:58,480
 will be the most PG-13 book in the entire Bible,

75
00:04:58,480 --> 00:05:01,400
 because in it we see things like idol worship,

76
00:05:01,400 --> 00:05:06,400
 violence, murder, child sacrifice, and even gang rape.

77
00:05:06,400 --> 00:05:10,120
 However, in the backdrop of Israel's complete failure

78
00:05:10,120 --> 00:05:11,980
 and their moral corruption,

79
00:05:11,980 --> 00:05:15,080
 we also see a glimpse of hope for the future.

80
00:05:15,080 --> 00:05:16,520
 And this hope for the future is something

81
00:05:16,520 --> 00:05:18,480
 that we will also be exploring

82
00:05:18,480 --> 00:05:20,080
 throughout this series as well.

83
00:05:21,000 --> 00:05:24,920
 (speaking in foreign language)

84
00:05:24,920 --> 00:05:49,160
 So structurally, the book of Judges

85
00:05:49,160 --> 00:05:52,080
 can be divided into three major section.

86
00:05:52,080 --> 00:05:53,760
 There is a double introduction,

87
00:05:53,760 --> 00:05:56,000
 there is a double conclusion at the end,

88
00:05:56,000 --> 00:05:58,640
 and in the middle of them is the cycle of Judges

89
00:05:58,640 --> 00:06:00,680
 where the author dive into the narrative

90
00:06:00,680 --> 00:06:03,240
 of these different judges of Israel.

91
00:06:03,240 --> 00:06:04,580
 And this morning we will focus

92
00:06:04,580 --> 00:06:07,120
 on the first introduction section.

93
00:06:07,120 --> 00:06:09,040
 And as we go through our passage today,

94
00:06:09,040 --> 00:06:11,680
 I want you all to keep this question in mind.

95
00:06:11,680 --> 00:06:14,920
 As God's people, are we becoming more and more

96
00:06:14,920 --> 00:06:17,480
 like the world around us?

97
00:06:17,480 --> 00:06:21,400
 (speaking in foreign language)

98
00:06:47,200 --> 00:06:50,000
 So let's look at Judges one together.

99
00:06:50,000 --> 00:06:54,040
 After the death of Joshua, the Israelites asked the Lord,

100
00:06:54,040 --> 00:06:58,320
 who of us is to go up first to fight against the Canaanites?

101
00:06:58,320 --> 00:07:00,960
 The Lord answered, Judah shall go up.

102
00:07:00,960 --> 00:07:03,080
 I have given the land into their hands.

103
00:07:03,080 --> 00:07:08,480
 (speaking in foreign language)

104
00:07:08,480 --> 00:07:12,400
 (speaking in foreign language)

105
00:07:12,400 --> 00:07:25,440
 So these first two verses here give us a clue

106
00:07:25,440 --> 00:07:29,240
 on where we are in terms of the history of Israel.

107
00:07:29,240 --> 00:07:30,760
 So let me give you a quick overview

108
00:07:30,760 --> 00:07:33,280
 of Israel history up to this point.

109
00:07:33,280 --> 00:07:34,800
 The events in the book of Judges

110
00:07:34,800 --> 00:07:38,880
 happened after the death of Joshua,

111
00:07:38,880 --> 00:07:42,040
 but before Israel had their first king.

112
00:07:42,040 --> 00:07:44,680
 And at this point, Israel is actually halfway

113
00:07:44,680 --> 00:07:47,720
 through taking over the land of Canaan.

114
00:07:47,720 --> 00:07:51,640
 (speaking in foreign language)

115
00:07:51,640 --> 00:07:55,560
 (speaking in foreign language)

116
00:07:55,560 --> 00:08:10,600
 So if you recall the covenant that God made

117
00:08:10,600 --> 00:08:14,640
 with your ancestor Abraham all the way back in Genesis 12,

118
00:08:14,640 --> 00:08:17,040
 God promised Abraham that he will make him

119
00:08:17,040 --> 00:08:20,400
 into a great nation, and all the people of the earth

120
00:08:20,400 --> 00:08:22,720
 will be blessed through him.

121
00:08:22,720 --> 00:08:26,000
 Besides, God would also give the land of Canaan

122
00:08:26,000 --> 00:08:29,120
 to Abraham's and his descendants.

123
00:08:29,120 --> 00:08:33,040
 (speaking in foreign language)

124
00:08:33,040 --> 00:08:48,360
 And when we come to the book of Deuteronomy,

125
00:08:48,360 --> 00:08:50,640
 we know that Israel, they finally arrived

126
00:08:50,640 --> 00:08:53,680
 at the edge of the promised land after they left Egypt

127
00:08:53,680 --> 00:08:56,360
 and wander in the wilderness for 40 years.

128
00:08:56,360 --> 00:08:57,960
 And at this point, they were getting ready

129
00:08:57,960 --> 00:08:59,840
 to take possession of the land.

130
00:08:59,840 --> 00:09:02,800
 So in Deuteronomy 20, we see that the Lord gave Israel

131
00:09:02,800 --> 00:09:06,320
 this command specifically about taking over the land.

132
00:09:06,320 --> 00:09:10,240
 (speaking in foreign language)

133
00:09:16,960 --> 00:09:17,800
 So this is it.

134
00:09:17,800 --> 00:09:20,200
 Deuteronomy 20, verse 16.

135
00:09:20,200 --> 00:09:22,360
 However, in the cities of the nations,

136
00:09:22,360 --> 00:09:25,400
 the Lord your God is giving you as inheritance,

137
00:09:25,400 --> 00:09:28,520
 do not leave alive anything that breathes.

138
00:09:28,520 --> 00:09:31,800
 Completely destroy them, the Hittites, the Amorites,

139
00:09:31,800 --> 00:09:35,840
 the Canaanites, the Perizzites, Hittites, and Jebusites,

140
00:09:35,840 --> 00:09:38,600
 as the Lord your God has commanded you.

141
00:09:38,600 --> 00:09:40,760
 Otherwise, they will teach you to follow

142
00:09:40,760 --> 00:09:44,080
 all the detestable things they do in worshiping their gods,

143
00:09:44,080 --> 00:09:47,000
 and you will sin against the Lord your God.

144
00:09:47,000 --> 00:09:52,480
 (speaking in foreign language)

145
00:09:52,480 --> 00:10:18,480
 And so just a few things to highlight here.

146
00:10:18,480 --> 00:10:20,400
 When we read a passage like this

147
00:10:20,400 --> 00:10:23,480
 to completely destroy any living things,

148
00:10:23,480 --> 00:10:25,200
 it should disturb us.

149
00:10:25,200 --> 00:10:26,640
 And it is totally normal for us

150
00:10:26,640 --> 00:10:28,920
 to wrestle with a passage like this.

151
00:10:28,920 --> 00:10:31,440
 But what we can know from the Bible

152
00:10:31,440 --> 00:10:34,080
 is that these people are not good people.

153
00:10:34,080 --> 00:10:35,640
 These people are evil.

154
00:10:35,640 --> 00:10:37,960
 There's a lot of immorality in these cities,

155
00:10:37,960 --> 00:10:40,200
 and they even practice child sacrifice

156
00:10:40,200 --> 00:10:42,080
 in their idol worship.

157
00:10:42,080 --> 00:10:58,800
 (speaking in foreign language)

158
00:10:58,800 --> 00:11:03,320
 And this is why the Lord specifically warned Israel

159
00:11:03,320 --> 00:11:07,080
 to completely destroy them, or in verse 18,

160
00:11:07,080 --> 00:11:09,960
 they will teach you to follow all the detestable things

161
00:11:09,960 --> 00:11:11,920
 they do in worshiping their gods,

162
00:11:11,920 --> 00:11:15,080
 and you will sin against the Lord your God.

163
00:11:15,080 --> 00:11:18,560
 In other words, it is to preserve the holiness of Israel

164
00:11:18,560 --> 00:11:21,200
 that God gave them this command.

165
00:11:21,200 --> 00:11:25,120
 (speaking in foreign language)

166
00:11:25,120 --> 00:11:39,360
 So that is Deuteronomy.

167
00:11:39,360 --> 00:11:41,280
 And when we come to the book of Joshua,

168
00:11:41,280 --> 00:11:44,640
 Israel began the conquest of this land of Canaan,

169
00:11:44,640 --> 00:11:47,760
 taking over the cities and settling into them.

170
00:11:47,760 --> 00:11:49,920
 And for the most part, the Joshua generations,

171
00:11:49,920 --> 00:11:52,640
 they remain pretty faithful to Yahweh.

172
00:11:52,640 --> 00:11:57,560
 (speaking in foreign language)

173
00:11:57,560 --> 00:12:06,280
 And so this is in Joshua 24.

174
00:12:06,280 --> 00:12:09,280
 Israel served the Lord throughout the lifetime of Joshua

175
00:12:09,280 --> 00:12:11,040
 and of the elders who outlived him

176
00:12:11,040 --> 00:12:12,640
 and who had experienced everything

177
00:12:12,640 --> 00:12:14,760
 the Lord had done for Israel.

178
00:12:14,760 --> 00:12:19,960
 (speaking in foreign language)

179
00:12:19,960 --> 00:12:33,160
 However, we also see some clues of potential challenge

180
00:12:33,160 --> 00:12:35,600
 during Israel conquest of the land.

181
00:12:35,600 --> 00:12:37,680
 As we see that some of the tribes of Israel,

182
00:12:37,680 --> 00:12:39,760
 they failed to completely drive out

183
00:12:39,760 --> 00:12:42,160
 these inhabitants of the land.

184
00:12:42,160 --> 00:12:46,080
 (speaking in foreign language)

185
00:12:46,080 --> 00:12:50,000
 And when we come to the book of Judges here,

186
00:12:50,000 --> 00:12:52,160
 this is where things begin to fall apart

187
00:12:52,160 --> 00:12:53,880
 for the people of Israel.

188
00:12:53,880 --> 00:12:58,240
 (speaking in foreign language)

189
00:12:58,240 --> 00:13:02,560
 And so the rest of the book of Judges chapter one

190
00:13:02,560 --> 00:13:05,360
 is sort of like a summary of how Israel fails

191
00:13:05,360 --> 00:13:07,520
 to follow God's instruction fully.

192
00:13:07,520 --> 00:13:10,560
 Both for the Northern tribes and the Southern tribes.

193
00:13:10,560 --> 00:13:14,480
 (speaking in foreign language)

194
00:13:14,480 --> 00:13:19,000
 So in Judges one, verse 19,

195
00:13:19,000 --> 00:13:22,240
 we see a summary of the conquest for the Southern tribe.

196
00:13:22,240 --> 00:13:25,800
 So verse 19, the Lord was with the men of Judah.

197
00:13:25,800 --> 00:13:28,080
 They took possessions of the hill country,

198
00:13:28,080 --> 00:13:31,480
 but they were unable to drive out the people

199
00:13:31,480 --> 00:13:34,720
 from the plains because they have chariots

200
00:13:34,720 --> 00:13:36,280
 fed with iron.

201
00:13:36,280 --> 00:13:37,320
 And just a quick side note here,

202
00:13:37,320 --> 00:13:39,920
 the iron chariot is actually not the real issue

203
00:13:39,920 --> 00:13:41,600
 for Israel's failure here.

204
00:13:41,600 --> 00:13:44,200
 Because later in the story of Deborah and Barak

205
00:13:44,200 --> 00:13:46,760
 in chapter four, we see that this iron chariot

206
00:13:46,760 --> 00:13:49,520
 is nothing against the Lord.

207
00:13:49,520 --> 00:13:53,080
 And then in verse 21, the Benjamites, however,

208
00:13:53,080 --> 00:13:55,480
 they did not drive out the Jebusites

209
00:13:55,480 --> 00:13:57,560
 who were living in Jerusalem.

210
00:13:57,560 --> 00:14:01,960
 To this day, the Jebusites live there with the Benjamites.

211
00:14:01,960 --> 00:14:05,880
 (speaking in foreign language)

212
00:14:05,880 --> 00:14:10,880
, and as for the Northern tribes,

213
00:14:10,880 --> 00:14:25,640
 the failures are also being summarized here.

214
00:14:25,640 --> 00:14:29,880
 (speaking in foreign language)

215
00:14:29,880 --> 00:14:34,240
 So verse 27, but Manasseh did not drive out the people,

216
00:14:34,240 --> 00:14:36,840
 nor did Ephraim drive out the Canaanites,

217
00:14:36,840 --> 00:14:39,480
 neither did Zebulun drive out the Canaanites,

218
00:14:39,480 --> 00:14:41,920
 nor did Asher drive out those living in

219
00:14:41,920 --> 00:14:43,720
 and in a specific location,

220
00:14:43,720 --> 00:14:46,120
 neither did Naphtali drive out.

221
00:14:46,120 --> 00:14:49,120
 And the Amorites confined the Danites to the hill country,

222
00:14:49,120 --> 00:14:52,040
 not allowing them to come down into the plain.

223
00:14:52,040 --> 00:14:56,880
 (speaking in foreign language)

224
00:14:56,880 --> 00:15:00,800
 (speaking in foreign language)

225
00:15:00,800 --> 00:15:17,320
 So if you're a visual learner, this next one is for you.

226
00:15:17,320 --> 00:15:20,280
 So the first image on the left is the extent of the land

227
00:15:20,280 --> 00:15:23,680
 that is being allotted to all the tribes of Israel.

228
00:15:23,680 --> 00:15:25,880
 And so this lands and these cities were given

229
00:15:25,880 --> 00:15:27,960
 to all 12 tribes of Israel.

230
00:15:27,960 --> 00:15:29,880
 However, they still have to do the work

231
00:15:29,880 --> 00:15:33,280
 of actually taking over these cities.

232
00:15:33,280 --> 00:15:37,200
 (speaking in foreign language)

233
00:15:37,200 --> 00:15:51,040
 And the image on the right, on the other hand,

234
00:15:51,040 --> 00:15:53,080
 shows the land and the cities that Israel

235
00:15:53,080 --> 00:15:57,360
 had successfully taken over by the time of judges.

236
00:15:57,360 --> 00:15:59,000
 And if you just compare these two image,

237
00:15:59,000 --> 00:16:00,520
 you can probably notice that there's actually

238
00:16:00,520 --> 00:16:03,160
 still a lot of land that Israel didn't manage

239
00:16:03,160 --> 00:16:04,440
 to take over, right?

240
00:16:04,440 --> 00:16:07,600
 Especially those along the plains by the Mediterranean Sea.

241
00:16:07,600 --> 00:16:12,600
 (speaking in foreign language)

242
00:16:21,800 --> 00:16:24,040
 So at this point, you might wonder,

243
00:16:24,040 --> 00:16:26,120
 why is this such a big deal that Israel

244
00:16:26,120 --> 00:16:28,480
 didn't manage to completely take over the land?

245
00:16:28,480 --> 00:16:31,080
 It seems like they had done a good job

246
00:16:31,080 --> 00:16:34,560
 in taking over most of the land, right?

247
00:16:34,560 --> 00:16:38,480
 (speaking in foreign language)

248
00:16:38,480 --> 00:16:46,880
 A lot of the time, we settle for half-hearted efforts.

249
00:16:46,880 --> 00:16:51,520
 As long as it is good enough, as long as I pass the exam,

250
00:16:51,520 --> 00:16:53,760
 or as long as I do the bare minimum.

251
00:16:53,760 --> 00:16:56,600
 And working with my students in Summit,

252
00:16:56,600 --> 00:16:59,080
 most of the time when I ask them to do something,

253
00:16:59,080 --> 00:17:02,160
 they usually respond with some half-hearted effort.

254
00:17:02,160 --> 00:17:07,000
 (speaking in foreign language)

255
00:17:07,000 --> 00:17:18,920
 Let me give you an example.

256
00:17:18,920 --> 00:17:20,480
 Usually during Summit, they will pull up

257
00:17:20,480 --> 00:17:22,960
 those ping pong table over there all the way back

258
00:17:22,960 --> 00:17:24,800
 in the auditorium to play, right?

259
00:17:24,800 --> 00:17:26,680
 And so after Summit, when I tell them

260
00:17:26,680 --> 00:17:30,080
 to put the ping pong table and everything away,

261
00:17:30,080 --> 00:17:32,240
 sometimes they might just fold up the table,

262
00:17:32,240 --> 00:17:35,480
 but still leave the table all the way back there.

263
00:17:35,480 --> 00:17:38,520
 And sometimes they will put the table at the right place,

264
00:17:38,520 --> 00:17:40,200
 but then they would just leave the paddle

265
00:17:40,200 --> 00:17:42,640
 and the net still all the way back there.

